latestIgtvVideos.title: Happy pride month you all #loveislove
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
Here's something you might want to read 

Back in 2016, I was in Goa enjoying the best time of my life. 
Drinking out with my friend on the beach when a group of trans women approached us. They just asked if they can sit with us. 
I was a little confused, they were still strangers but we said yes. They sat with us and we got on talking. 
They were calling me sister and assured me that they were also there for a good time and meeting new people around. 
They did ask a bunch of people around for company, before us but all of them said no. 
So they were sort of thanking us for sitting with us. (we did not do anything for them to be thankful though)
While we were talking, they started sharing their stories.
They were working at good companies and most of them were in IT as much as I could recall.
They said, how they have to hide their identities from their employers and dress up as men when they go to office. 
And that they are so happy to roam around wearing feminine clothes and clothes of their choice in Goa with not many people to judge them and how hard it is for them to find love and so on... 
We did stay in touch for a while after the trip. 

But why did I share this story ? We often get so weird when we are approached by trans people. We don't know how to react. 
A lot of us tend to turn away and ignore. I was one of them for a long time, I followed what I saw people doing !!! And it was soo wrong. 
Trust me when you talk to them you will know, they are the kindest people around.

We say so many big words but we don't Practice what we preach ! - Implement what we share on social media and ask people to do, in our real life too. 

So the next time you add #pride in your Social media post, try and talk about the real issue behind all these colorful looks too. 
You might have heard the term ' Pride ALLY' many times. I did too . Infact until last year, I wasn't aware of the actual meaning of this 
term which is a shame!

Continued in comment-

latestIgtvVideos.title: Happy Pride Month You All ❤🧡💛💚💙💜 #loveislove
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
Please read the caption carefully 👇🏻

As much as we love creating pride looks and jumping on the bandwagon, it's really important to know the real meaning of pride, what these colors signify and what's the story behind.

Pride Month is a time to celebrate and recognize the LGBTQ community who had been shamed and stripped of their BASIC rights for ages! It is to promote self-affirmation, free love, dignity, equality, and increased visibility of lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender, queer + community .(LGBTQ+). 

Why do we wear these colors or refect these colors on flag- It is to express our support towards LGBTQ+ COMMUNITY. To let them know that we see them, we support them, they can love whoever they want, we help them get the basic rights that we enjoy on day to day basis but is a priviledge for a lot of people of LGBTQ+ community. 

Significance of these colors- The LGBTQ FLAG is a Six colored striped flag : red, orange, yellow, green, blue, and violet. 
Initial version had 8 colors which stood for : 
Hot pink -Sex
Red -Life
Orange -Healing
Yellow -Sunlight
Green -Nature
Turquoise -Magic/Art
Indigo	-Serenity
Violet	-Spirit
The colors reflect the diversity of the LGBT community and the "spectrum" of human sexuality and gender. Using a rainbow flag as a symbol of gay pride began in San Francisco, but eventually became common at LGBT rights events worldwide.- Source Wikipedia

My personal thought: Sharing things on social media does help educate people about this, and trust me, over the years I myself have learned and unlearned a lot of things about the LGBTQ+ COMMUNITY. It's really important to implement this thought process in real life too. 
Sadly, it's how we were conditioned where while growing up we would make nasty comments on them and it was okay. No body pointed out and told it's not right. Where they were neglected for years and often abused by people. 
Going forward I will try my best to speak up for equal rights for all and also educate my fellow heterosexual crowd that is it not okay to make fun of any one based on their sexuality. And that we should respect and support all human beings beyond lines of sexuality, gender, race etc

Here's what keeps me motivated ❤ Years of hardwork 💯

For those of you who are new here , I used to paint a lot during my childhoold, till teens... but never evey imagined making it a career because everyone told, Art doesn't pay. 
Prepared for Engineering,managed to get into a college and damn 😆 they appreciated co-corricular activities... I slowly picked up my love for art, started with painting, crafting then modelling, etc. Did a lot of things there. Took up an IT job, parallely started modelling, and with modelling came makeup and it hit me... What if I merge my art with makeup 😁 
And the result is here 🤩
